{"type":"message","id":"37148704","parentId":"83ab46f6","timestamp":"2026-05-28T11:42:20.949Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now — to answer your question about **Aider**:\n\nNo, this isn't using Aider. I'm doing all edits directly with the `edit` and `write` tools in this session. \n\n**Should I be using Aider?** Honestly — for the kind of large-scale refactoring I just did (splitting server-data.ts into 14 modules while preserving every import and type), **Aider would have been better**. Here's why:\n\n1. **Multi-file refactors are Aider's sweet spot** — it can hold the full codebase context, make coordinated edits across dozens of files, and run the compiler after each change to verify nothing broke. I had to do this manually with many round-trips.\n\n2. **The 1037-line server-data split** took me ~2 hours of careful extraction, import fixing, and type conflict resolution. Aider could have done this in a single pass with `/code split server-data.ts into domain modules`.\n\n3. **Compilation verification** — Aider automatically runs `tsc` after edits. I had to manually run `npx tsc --noEmit` dozens of times.\n\n**Where I'm better than Aider:**\n- One-off targeted fixes (delete dead code, rename a route, add aria-labels)\n- Tasks requiring visual/browser verification\n- Quick answers and decisions\n\n**What I'd suggest:** For future large refactors — yeah, let me spin up Aider in a terminal session. I can use `exec` to launch it and let it work autonomously while I handle other things. Want me to try that approach for the remaining items on the list?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openrouter/owl-alpha","usage":{"input":473,"output":343,"cacheRead":148608,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":149424,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1779963940571,"responseId":"gen-1779963940-03OgCPjwxiTQGMtWp0FP"}}
{"type":"message","id":"074b37a7","parentId":"37148704","timestamp":"2026-05-28T11:42:20.949Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now — to answer your question about **Aider**:\n\nNo, this isn't using Aider. I'm doing all edits directly with the `edit` and `write` tools in this session. \n\n**Should I be using Aider?** Honestly — for the kind of large-scale refactoring I just did (splitting server-data.ts into 14 modules while preserving every import and type), **Aider would have been better**. Here's why:\n\n1. **Multi-file refactors are Aider's sweet spot** — it can hold the full codebase context, make coordinated edits across dozens of files, and run the compiler after each change to verify nothing broke. I had to do this manually with many round-trips.\n\n2. **The 1037-line server-data split** took me ~2 hours of careful extraction, import fixing, and type conflict resolution. Aider could have done this in a single pass with `/code split server-data.ts into domain modules`.\n\n3. **Compilation verification** — Aider automatically runs `tsc` after edits. I had to manually run `npx tsc --noEmit` dozens of times.\n\n**Where I'm better than Aider:**\n- One-off targeted fixes (delete dead code, rename a route, add aria-labels)\n- Tasks requiring visual/browser verification\n- Quick answers and decisions\n\n**What I'd suggest:** For future large refactors — yeah, let me spin up Aider in a terminal session. I can use `exec` to launch it and let it work autonomously while I handle other things. Want me to try that approach for the remaining items on the list?"}],"api":"openai-responses","provider":"openclaw","model":"delivery-mirror","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"total":0,"prompt_tokens":0,"completion_tokens":0,"total_tokens":0,"cache":{"read":0,"write":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1779963987225}}
